PHASE 2 - CHUNKING

1.Fixed Size Chunking - You just count characters or tokens and cut at a fixed number, with some overlap between chunks so you don't lose context at the boundaries.

"The capybara is the largest rodent. It lives in South America. 
 It is semi-aquatic. It weighs up to 65kg..."

Chunk 1: "The capybara is the largest rodent. It lives in South America."
Chunk 2: "It lives in South America. It is semi-aquatic."  ← overlap
Chunk 3: "It is semi-aquatic. It weighs up to 65kg..."    ← overlap

Pros: Simple, fast, predictable, easy to implement
Cons: Completely ignores the meaning of the text. Can cut right in the middle of an important idea. A chunk might start mid-sentence or mid-topic.

2. Recursive Character Splitting

First try to split at:  \n\n  (paragraph breaks)
If chunks still too big, split at:  \n  (line breaks)
If still too big, split at:  .  (sentences)
If still too big, split at:  " "  (words)
As last resort, split at character level

Document text: 
"The capybara is the largest rodent in the world.

It is native to South America. The capybara is a highly 
social animal that lives in groups."

Chunk 1: "The capybara is the largest rodent in the world."
Chunk 2: "It is native to South America. The capybara is a highly social animal that lives in groups."

Pros: Respects natural text boundaries, produces more coherent chunks than fixed size, still fast
Cons: Still based on character counts, does not actually understand the meaning of the text

3. Semantic Chunking -Instead of splitting based on character counts or punctuation, it splits based on meaning.

Split the text into individual sentences first
Embed each sentence into a vector
Calculate the similarity between consecutive sentences
When similarity drops significantly, that is a topic change — split there

Sentence 1: "The capybara is the largest rodent."         similarity: 0.92 ← similar topic, keep together
Sentence 2: "It can weigh up to 65 kilograms."            similarity: 0.89 ← similar topic, keep together  
Sentence 3: "Capybaras live near water sources."          similarity: 0.45 ← BIG DROP, split here!
Sentence 4: "They are found across South America."        similarity: 0.87 ← similar topic, keep together
Sentence 5: "Countries include Brazil and Argentina."

Pros: Produces the most meaningful and coherent chunks, each chunk tends to be about one specific topic
Cons: Much slower because it needs to embed every sentence, requires an embedding model to run during chunking, more complex to implement

Semantic — best quality chunks but slowest
Recursive — good quality, fast, used most often in real projects
Fixed size — lowest quality but simplest


